<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Segni on Pact Differences With Berlusconi Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Segni on Pact Differences With Berlusconi Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204094594 Rome RAI Uno Television Network in Italian 1800 
GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204094594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Uno Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Italian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Studio interview with Mario Segni, leader of the Pact for </F>
Italy, by Bruno Vespa on 21 April -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Vespa] Mr. Segni, it seems that everyone is 
sticking to their position. Some of you, a small number, want 
to abstain from voting against the government, while the 
majority want to be in opposition. 
  [Segni] Yes, that is the situation. A Berlusconi government 
is being viewed in different ways. Of course, that does not 
prevent us from working together in parliament or looking to the 
forthcoming European elections. 
  [Vespa] But if the four MP's who want to abstain from voting 
against Berlusconi do abstain, will they be allowed to stay in 
the Pact for Italy or will they be thrown out? 
  [Segni] We will deal with this if it occurs; I do not know 
what would happen. However, the important thing is to explain 
the reasons for our positions concerning Berlusconi. It is not 
a preconceived position. There are some matters which must be 
settled before a favorable judgment can be made. 

</TEXT>

