<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bundesbank Lowers Money Market Rate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bundesbank Lowers Money Market Rate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2104124994 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE in German 
21 Apr 94 p 15 </F>

<F P=103> AU2104124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["gb" report: "Bundesbank Lowers Money Market Rate"] </F>
  [Text] Frankfurt/Main, 20 Apr -- On Wednesday [20 April] 
the German Bundesbank allocated to the business banks new 
financial means at an interest rate of 5.58 percent within the 
framework of its weekly money market business. Last week this 
interest rate had been 5.7 percent and the week before 5.73 
percent. The slightly faster decline of the so-called "third 
prime rate" was no surprise to most participants in the market, 
after the Bundesbank had reduced the two traditional interest 
rates, the discount rate and the Lombard rate, last Thursday [14 
April]. A few hours after the allocation by the Bundesbank, the 
Belgian National Bank announced a reduction of its money market 
rate from 5.8 to 5.7 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

