<F P=100> PORTUGAL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Barroso Urges Support for Mozambique Peace Process </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Barroso Urges Support for Mozambique Peace Process </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104140094 Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network in Portuguese 
1300 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2104140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Portuguese Foreign Minister Durao 
Barroso has called on the international community not to abandon 
Mozambique in the current phase of the peace process. Durao 
Barroso met Renamo [Mozambique National Resistance] leader 
Afonso Dhlakama earlier this afternoon. The former is concerned 
about the withdrawal of a number of countries from the UN 
contingent in Mozambique. It should be recalled that Italy 
recently withdrew half of its men. 
  [Begin recording] [Barroso] We must draw attention to what 
is 
happening in Mozambique, because unfortunately there are cases 
where it is only when things go wrong that people remember. 
Recently we have seen tragic cases in Africa. The case now of 
Rwanda is a tragic case -- tens of thousands of deaths. 
Therefore, we think it is better to try to prevent things 
rather than to act a posteriori. Indeed, a contribution to the 
formation of the armed forces, and not just the armed forces but 
also the demobilized men, a contribution to social 
reintegration, even emergency aid in some areas, would be a way 
of consolidating this process. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] Durao Barroso also presented a list of support 
measures Portugal is taking to help the Mozambican electoral 
process. The cost of maintaining the 4th Army battalion alone 
is estimated at nearly 7 billion escudos. Afonso Dhlakama will 
take back to Renamo about 50 million escudos for the electoral 
campaign, from the Lisbon government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

