<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prolongation of Talks Deemed Unacceptable </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prolongation of Talks Deemed Unacceptable </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2104143994 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2104143994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Government spokesman Ioannis Kasoulidhis today 
stressed that if the efforts to reach an agreement have failed 
by the end of next week, then everyone who is interested in the 
Cyprus issue must conclude that the Turkish side has no 
political desire for a solution on either the 
confidence-building measures or the substance of the Cyprus 
issue. The spokesman concluded: Therefore, the way the issues 
are handled following this evaluation will have consequences 
that might even extend the status quo. 
  Kasoulidhis stressed that the government will not let the 
issue dominate efforts to solve the Cyprus problem. He said: 
One year is more than enough. 
  Answering questions, the spokesman reiterated that the Greek 
Cypriot side insists on the 21 March UN document on the 
confidence-building measures.. He added that yesterday's 
meeting between President Glavkos Kliridhis and Gustave Feissel, 
the UN secretary general's alternate special representative in 
Cyprus, does not fall within the framework of proximity talks 
but is part of customary meetings. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

