<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cindoruk, Croatian Officials Discuss Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cindoruk, Croatian Officials Discuss Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2204080294 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2204080294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Husamettin Cindoruk, speaker of the Turkish Grand 
National Assembly [TGNA], has said that those who have the power 
to stop the massacre in Bosnia-Herzegovina but do not do so are 
as responsible as those who actually perpetrate the massacre. 
  Cindoruk received Zarko Domljan, chairman of the Croatian 
Parliament Foreign Affairs Committee, and his delegation today. 
Cindoruk stressed at the meeting that the Serbs will not escape 
their destiny as the unjust party in history and in the eyes of 
the world. A massacre of this nature in the middle of Europe 
during a civilized age in history is unacceptable, he said, 
adding that murdering defenseless people is also a bad example 
for other parts of the world. The TGNA speaker asked: On the 
eve of the 21st century, is Europe returning to its feudal 
structure of the Middle Ages? 
  Cindoruk stressed that the United Nations and NATO failed to 
display the required determination in the face of Serbian 
aggression. Unless the attacks are stopped, he said, the 
effectiveness of these organizations will be in doubt. 
  The TGNA speaker also said that the Serbian attacks violate 
the Paris Charter and the Human Rights Declaration and strip 
them of their importance. He added that the agreement between 
the Croats and the Bosnians constitutes an important step toward 
the solution of the problem by peaceful means. 
  In turn, Domljan said that the Croats have always maintained 
that Bosnia-Herzegovina should have its independence and 
territorial integrity. We are opposed to the forcible change of 
borders or to the occupation of territory, he said. 
  Before meeting with Cindoruk, the Croatian parliamentary 
delegation visited Erdal Inonu, chairman of the TGNA Foreign 
Relations Committee, and Baki Tug, chairman of the TGNA National 
Defense Committee. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

