<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> United Kingdom </F>
<H3> <TI>   Industry Chief Attacks `Intrusive' EU Legislation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Industry Chief Attacks `Intrusive' EU Legislation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2004110494 London FINANCIAL TIMES in English 20 Apr 94 p 7 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PM2004110494 </F>
<F P=104>  London FINANCIAL TIMES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Ian Hamilton Fazey article: "CBI Chief Hints at `Risible' </F>
Euro Laws"] 
  [Text] The Confederation of British Industry [CBI] plans to 
develop a Europe-wide business agenda to unite EU [European 
Union] business leaders in resisting intrusive social 
legislation, Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the 
Confederation of British Industry, said last night. Attacking 
"ill-conceived," "disappointing," and "risible" policies in 
Brussels and among EU member governments, Mr Davies told the 
annual dinner of the Yorkshire and Humberside regional CBI that 
EU legislation on social policy was being brought into disrepute. 
  It was time for the European business community to act in 
its 
common interest and force politicians to take notice. The CBI's 
business agenda would be published next month. 
  Mr Davies said recent "disappointing developments" in Europe 
include: 
  1. EU member governments' discussions of a white paper on 
growth, competitiveness and employment by Mr Jacques Delors, the 
European Commission president, were focusing on new social 
policy initiatives and running counter to the document's 
original themes. 
  2. A green paper on social policy which had focused on ways 
of increasing the cost of employing labour instead of how to get 
Europe's 20 million jobless back to work. 
  3. Failure by the EU and the Council of Ministers to prevent 
a proliferation of state aid for steel, telecommunications 
energy and air travel, putting British companies at a 
disadvantage. 
  4. The failure of the EU to get to grips with its spending. 
Auditors had produced "dismal catalogues of fraud and waste", 
yet the commission took little interest. 
  All large European employers opposed the European Works 
Council Directive -- discussed yesterday by the Council of 
Ministers -- said Mr Davies, because it would cut across 
existing satisfactory consultation arrangements, impose new 
administrative burdens, push up costs and slow down 
decision-making. 
  Britain was not obliged to follow it because of its opt-out 
from the Maastricht social chapter, but 90 UK companies would be 
affected in mainland Europe and the EU was funding a union 
campaign to persuade companies which were not affected by the 
directive to follow it voluntarily. 
  He dismissed the commission's claim that the directive would 
increase identification of employees with their companies and 
increase productivity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-19805 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu078__a94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-076-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel: `Basic Agreement' to U.S. Bosnian Initiative </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel: `Basic Agreement' to U.S. Bosnian Initiative </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204070794 Hamburg DPA in German 2136 GMT 21 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2204070794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington (DPA) -- FRG Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel has indicated the possibility that NATO might extend a 
ban on heavy weapons -- along the line of the Sarajevo model -- 
only to Gorazde and not to all safe areas in Bosnia. "It could 
be that first a decision will be made in connection with 
Gorazde," Kinkel said on Thursday evening [21 April] after talks 
in Washington with his U.S. counterpart Warren Christopher and 
U.S. National Security Adviser Anthony Lake. 
  In addition, the minister expressed doubts about U.S. ideas 
of tightening sanctions against Serbia. He has "announced 
doubts that we can further tighten the screw," Kinkel said, 
referring to the effects of the sanctions on countries such as 
Bulgaria, Hungary, Romania, and Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM]. 
  On Wednesday, U.S. President Bill Clinton had suggested a 
united course against the Bosnian Serbs to bring them back to 
the negotiating table and to save the Muslim enclave of Gorazde. 
The United States wants to win over the Western allies and 
Russia for banning heavy weapons in the surroundings of the 
other five UN safe areas, following the example of Sarajevo. 
Otherwise, the Serbs must expect NATO air raids. 
  Kinkel stressed the "basic agreement" to the U.S. Bosnian 
initiative. In addition to the military plans, it is absolutely 
necessary to push ahead the political process and to include 
Russia. He assessed the Russian suggestion of a summit with 
restraint. Such a conference should be held only if success is 
relatively certain, Kinkel said. 
  Apart from Bosnia, Germany's presidency in the European 
Union, which begins on 1 July, was one of the focal points of 
Kinkel's talks. He announced close cooperation with the 
Americans in the fields of environmental protection, combating 
crime, drug trafficking, and terrorism, as well as disarmament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

