<H3> <TI>   Kohl Expects No Unemployment Decrease in 1994 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kohl Expects No Unemployment Decrease in 1994 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004202694 Hamburg DPA in German 1822 GMT 20 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2004202694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chemnitz (DPA) -- Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl, 
of the Christian Democratic Union [CDU], does not expect the 
economic recovery to lead to a reduction of unemployment in 
Germany this year. "I would be satisfied if we managed to stop 
unemployment this year," Kohl said on Wednesday [20 April] night 
at a conference sponsored by FREIE PRESSE in Chemnitz. That was 
all one could expect from the current developments. 
  In his approximately one-hour lecture, Kohl emphasized that 
economic recovery in the new laender had started: "Although the 
flourishing landscapes will not come within four or five years, 
they are on their way," he said. 
  Kohl said that it was a "very tough experience" to see how 
difficult the Germans were finding it to achieve internal unity. 
The chancellor said that people in both east and west obviously 
became more alienated than had been thought. 

</TEXT>

