BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "More Undecided Voters Than Ever"] </F>
  [Text] There are now more voters who are undecided about 
which party to vote for than ever before. As many as 26 percent 
of voters do not know which party they will vote for on 3 May. 
Even more voters (29 percent) have recently changed their minds 
on how they will vote. 
  These are the findings of the NSS survey bureau in The 
Hague. 
The survey bureau attributes the high percentage of undecided 
voters to great restlessness and uncertainty among voters. At 
present, it is the Center Democrats (and CP86 [Central Party 
86]) and the Elderly People's Party which are benefitting most 
from this uncertainty. The latest opinion poll conducted by NSS 
gives them respectively, six and five seats . 
  According to the bureau in The Hague, the main reasons why 
people are switching parties are the reports and developments 
regarding social security and problems concerning foreigners and 
asylum-seekers. 
  The PvdA [Labor Party] can expect 33 seats, the CDA 
[Christian Democrat Party], and the D66 [Democrats 66] 28 seats 
each, while the VVD [People's Party for Freedom and Democracy] 
could grow to 27 representatives, the NSS poll indicates. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

