<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dependents, Nonessential Staff To Leave Belgrade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dependents, Nonessential Staff To Leave Belgrade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204193094 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1839 GMT 22 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204193094 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Britain is withdrawing a number of staff from its 
embassy in Belgrade, capital of the war-torn former Yugoslavia, 
the Foreign Office confirmed tonight. 
  Dependents of embassy officials and other non-essential 
members of staff will leave as "a sensible precaution," a 
spokesman said. 
  "The embassy will remain open, but operating at a reduced 
level," he added. 
  The embassy was also reported to be contacting all British 
and Commonwealth nationals registered with it. "If anyone wants 
to leave at the same time they can come with our convoy," First 
Secretary David Campbell told REUTERS in Belgrade. 
  The Foreign Office said the withdrawal of personnel was "a 
sensible precaution because of increased tension". 
  There are 11 British diplomats at the Belgrade embassy, 
which 
will remain open but probably with a reduced number of staff. 
  The evacuees, expected to number less than 20, will leave by 
road convoy -- possibly tomorrow. 
  Elsewhere in Belgrade there are about 60 other British 
residents, most of them journalists or married to local people. 
  The Foreign Office issued advice some time ago for British 
nationals to leave the city. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

