<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tietmeyer Says Bundesbank Satisfied With Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tietmeyer Says Bundesbank Satisfied With Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204194794 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 22 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU2204194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["bf" report: "Monetary Policy `Does Not Prevent' Recovery"] </F>
  [Excerpt] Duesseldorf, 21 Apr -- In the view of its 
president, Hans Tietmeyer, the Bundesbank can be satisfied with 
its policy. In the introduction to the annual report Tietmeyer 
writes that the central bank has carefully sounded out the 
existing margin in a difficult situation. With the slowing down 
of the persistent inflation and the resulting positive 
developments on the financial markets, the preconditions for an 
"appropriate and lasting" economic growth have improved 
decisively. "Monetary policy did not and does not prevent the 
process of economic recovery." 
  A "short-winded" monetary policy, which would have reduced 
the central bank interest rates aggressively and without 
consideration for the reemerging expectations of inflation, 
would hardly be so successful. "Cautious action, aimed at 
making positive expectations permanent, was, in the end, also in 
the interest of the other European countries." Also with a view 
to the second stage of the European Monetary Union, which has 
already begun, no doubts must arise about the orientation of 
German monetary policy toward stability. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

