<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kassoulidhis Comments on Clinton's Cyprus Statement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kassoulidhis Comments on Clinton's Cyprus Statement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2304113794 Nicosia CYPRUS NEWS AGENCY in English 1009 GMT 
23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2304113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia CYPRUS NEWS AGENCY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nicosia, Apr 23 (CNA)--The Cyprus Government 
welcomed with skepticism a statement by U.S. President Bill 
Clinton, who expressed the hope that there would be some 
movement from the Turkish side on Cyprus in the next couple of 
days with regard to the U.N.-proposed package of 
confidence-building measures (CBM'S). 
  Government spokesman Ioannis Kassoulidhis told the Cyprus 
News Agency Saturday [23 April] that "really President Clinton 
has shown personal interest" in the efforts for a Cyprus 
settlement. 
  "He (Clinton) correctly noted that the ball has been in 
Denktas's court," the spokesman said. 
  Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas has so far refused to 
accept the U.N.-proposed CBM's package while President Glavkos 
Kliridhis has accepted it in principle since May 1993. 
  Spokesman Kassoulidhis said he would not make further 
comments "until we really see that Mr Denktas has accepted the 
21 March document" of the United Nations regarding the 
implementation of the CBM's 
  Asked "what about Cyprus" before his White House talks 
Friday 
with Greek prime minister Andreas Papandreou, President Clinton 
said: 
  "We're working hard on Cyprus, and I think, I hope there 
will 
be some movement from the Turkish side on Cyprus in the next 
couple of days with regard to the confidence-building measures. 
I think that the ball has been sort of in Mr. Denktas's court, 
and I hope he will take it up, and then I hope that Greece and 
all others will support pushing forward. I have worked hard to 
resolve this since I've been in office, and I will continue to 
stay on it." 
  Speaking during a press conference after his talks with 
Premier Papandreou, the U.S. President said the U.S. "supports 
the U.N. confidence-building measures. Those measures grew out 
of discussions with President Kliridhis soon after he took 
office, and we hope that both sides will support them." 
  He said his coordinator for Cyprus Robert Lamb had just 
returned from talks with both sides. 
  He said "A settlement in Cyprus would benefit all the 
nations 
in the region, especially Greece and Turkey, two vital members 
of NATO." 
  President Clinton pledged to do what he can "to promote 
greater understanding between these two critical nations and, in 
the process, to promote progress on Cyprus." 
  Meanwhile, U.N envoys on Cyprus were due Saturday to start a 
new effort to try to convince the Turkish side to accept the 
CBM'S. 
  U.N. secretary-general's special representative Joe Clark 
was 
scheduled to meet Saturday in Washington Greece's Foreign 
Minister Karolos Papoulias, who is accompanying premier 
Papandreou on his U.S. trip. 
  On Sunday, the former Canadian prime minister will fly to 
Ankara for talks with the Turkish Government. He will be joined 
in the Turkish capital by the U.N. chief's resident 
representative to Cyprus Gustave Feissel. 
  The U.N. envoys will come to Cyprus on Wednesday for talks 
with President Kliridhis and Rauf Denktas. 
  Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops 
invaded and occupied 37 per cent of its territory. 
  Among the confidence-building measures proposed by the U.N. 
is the transfer of part of the Turkish-occupied town of 
Famagusta to the U.N. administration to allow some 16.000 Greek 
Cypriot refugees to return to their homes and the re-opening of 
the now defunct Nicosia International Airport. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

