<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papandreou `Especially Satisfied' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papandreou `Especially Satisfied' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2404111394 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 0900 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2404111394 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou said he was 
especially satisfied with the outcome of his official talks with 
U.S. President Bill Clinton. Athens News Agency reported today 
from Washington that after meeting U.S. Senator Paul Sarbanes 
and U.S. Presidential Adviser George Stephanopoulos, the prime 
minister said he is optimistic about the issue of Skopje [The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM]. Papandreou 
stressed that many opposing forces operate in politics and no 
one can predict developments with certainty. 
  Papandreou added that in the United States he found a very 
warm welcome and support for Greece and noted that for the first 
time it was recognized that Greece has rights that are being 
violated. Discussing Greek-Turkish relations, the prime minister 
said that Washington is under the impression that the 
possibilities for positive Greek-Turkish relations are greater 
than we think. 
  In light of Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias' meeting with 
international mediator Cyrus Vance in New York, U.S. 
Presidential envoy to Skopje Matthew Nimetz met Foreign Ministry 
Secretary General Ambassador Khristos Zakharakis at the Greek 
Embassy. 
  The official part of Papandreou's visit to Washington 
concluded last night with a reception hosted by the Greek 
ambassador at the Embassy. The prime minister and his 
delegation will leave for New York today. 

</TEXT>

