<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman on Reference to National Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman on Reference to National Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2304204594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1700 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2304204594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos commented 
in Thessaloniki today on the prime minister's [U.S.] visit. Our 
correspondent Foivos Karzis has the following report. 
  [Begin recording] [Venizelos] I believe that the statement 
made by President Clinton to the journalists is satisfactory 
with regard to all the issues concerning us -- that is, 
primarily on the Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia--FYROM] issue, Greek-Albanian relations, the 
Patriarchate's position, and the prospects of the Cyprus issue. 
It is a significant fact that President Clinton recognizes the 
Greek sensitivities and, if you like, the soundness of the Greek 
position and that he attaches so much importance to Cyrus 
Vance's mission and that of Matthew Nimetz, who will be coming 
to supplement the Vance mission. 
  [Karzis] On Albania, Athens is waiting for the upcoming 
crucial Papoulias-Serreqi meeting while taking continuous steps 
to protect the Greek minority. 
  [Venizelos] The protection of the Greek minority's rights is 
a self-evident prerequisite, respect for international law and 
human rights is non-negotiable; and this, of course, concerns 
all the levels at which this issue is raised. 
  [Karzis] Concerning Greek-Turkish relations, Mr. Venizelos 
said that Greece must be sparing and careful when referring to 
Turkey's internal political problems. However, he pointed out 
that Ankara is trying to export these problems. 
  [Venizelos] What concerns us about the recent local 
elections 
in Turkey is that we hope there are no provocations, no 
violations of international law, and that the historic existence 
and international status of the Ecumenical Patriarchate is 
respected. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

