<DOCNO> FBIS4-19884 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu079_p_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Political Parties Comment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Political Parties Comment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2404064794 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2404064794 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Opposition parties are waiting before they assess 
the Papandreou-Clinton meeting in the White House yesterday, 
while the left wing considers the results negative. 
  New Democracy Chairman Miltiadhis Evert said that the visit 
has been neutral--neither positive nor negative--and this has 
caused some optimism in the Greek delegation. Mr. Evert noted 
that we have received more pressure on the Bosnian and Turkish 
issues and that the Greek prime minister did not succeed in 
convincing the Americans to put pressure on Skopje [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM]. He added: I believe 
that tomorrow's meeting between Mr. Karolos Papoulias and Mr. 
Cyrus Vance will be important; we will see how the situation 
develops. Mr. Evert concluded: It is a colorless visit with 
compliments and nice speeches, but I have not as yet seen any 
results. 
  Political Spring Chairman Andonios Samaras said: Despite the 
dangerous concessions and serious vagueness that appeared at 
yesterday's news conference, I would not like to make my 
positions known in public so long as the country's prime 
minister is abroad. I will wait for his return and his briefing 
of the opposition. Mr. Samaras concluded: The only thing I can 
say now is that I am deeply concerned. 
  Former Prime Minister Konstandinos Mitsotakis made a 
statement today referring to the question of Skopje's name. He 
said: Nobody can deny that it is better to be named North 
Macedonia or New Macedonia rather than plain Macedonia. There 
is no doubt about this. As soon as Mitsotakis' statement became 
known, New Democracy Chairman Miltiadhis Evert responded: New 
Democracy's positions are known and firm. 
  The Greek Communist Party has assessed that the prime 
minister's visit to the United States marks and seals Greece's 
full submission to the U.S. aggressive and warlike policy in the 
Balkans and the eastern Mediterranean. This policy aims at 
converting this region, at any cost, into a zone of U.S. 
interests and influence. 
  Commenting on the statements by the Greek prime minister and 
the U.S. President, the Coalition of the Left and of Progress 
Party points out, among other things, that excessive 
expectations are being cultivated once again about the 
development of our national issues for reasons of domestic 
consumption. Unfortunately, the party statement adds, Mr. 
Papandreou's belated pro-American turn continues to be based on 
self-illusions about the role and aims of the U.S. policy on the 
Balkans. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-19885 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu079_p_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Mostly `Positive' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks Mostly `Positive' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2304190694 Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA in Greek 23 Apr 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> NC2304190694 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ELEVTHEROTIPIA </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [The "Views" column: "Initial Appraisals"] </F>
  [Text] Given the hitherto negative, almost hostile, 
atmosphere and our fear of a lack of U.S. understanding of Greek 
affairs, we must conclude that rather positive results, as well 
as some other disturbing puzzles for the Cyprus issue and 
Greek-Turkish relations, have emerged from the talks between 
Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou and U.S. President Bill 
Clinton. 
  It is positive that President Clinton recognized that 
Greece's concern over the Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic 
of Macedonia--FYROM] issue was justified, stressing that these 
concerns "have their roots in ancient and modern history." 
  It is positive that Clinton said "We are concerned about the 
Greek minority in Albania" and pointed out that Greece is 
addressing the problem "with wisdom and sound judgment." 
  It is positive that President Clinton expressed his interest 
in the Ecumenical Patriarchate to the Turkish prime minister. 
  It is positive that the road is open for Greek-U.S. economic 
cooperation aimed at their business infiltration into the 
Balkans. 
  This cooperation is backed-up by the U.S. with $1 billion, 
which shows their recognition of Greece's role in the region and 
its possibilities for peace initiatives. 
  It is not easy to appraise the practical results of these 
initially positive elements now because certainly things were 
said at the talks which were not announced at the joint news 
conference. 
  The Cyprus issue remains a puzzle as President Clinton 
referred to the mediator for its solution, and Andreas 
Papandreou merely said that there is "good news" about the 
promotion of the confidence-building measures. 
  Greek-Turkish affairs also remain a puzzle -- except for the 
Patriarchate issue. President Clinton expressed his wishes for 
Greek-Turkish cooperation; he pointed out the Turkish 
Government's concern over the increase of Islamism, and asked 
Greece to contribute to European assistance to Turkey and to 
cooperate with it. However, he did not say what Turkey, which 
constantly provokes Greece, should do. 
  At any rate, the meeting showed that there are grounds for 
further understanding and development of Greek-U.S. relations 
and, with all the necessary reservations, this is rather 
positive. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-19886 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu079_p_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Remarks on Skopje, Cyprus Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton Remarks on Skopje, Cyprus Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2304184994 Athens I KATHIMERINI in Greek 23 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> NC2304184994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens I KATHIMERINI </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Hopes From the Meeting"] </F>
  [Text] The meeting between U.S. President Bill Clinton and 
Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou confirmed the positive 
atmosphere in our bilateral relations which might even affect 
pending issues in our national policy -- the Cyprus and Skopje 
[The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] issues. 
  Mr. Bill Clinton created expectations on the Greek side when 
he told journalists that there must be some changes in Skopje's 
views and when he gave assurances of his personal interest in 
the Cyprus issue, expressing the hope that there might be some 
movement by the Turkish Cypriot side to accept the 
confidence-building measures [CBM's] in the next few days. 
  The U.S. interest in stability in the region should be 
considered obvious. It is also obvious that stability is not 
feasible unless there is relaxation in Greece's disputes with 
Turkey and the Republic of Skopje. Naturally, since all sides 
have declared their intentions to resolve their disputes through 
dialogue, any settlement that is reached can only be a 
compromise. 
  Concerning the Cyprus issue the Greek side, by accepting the 
proposals on the CBM's, has made further concessions and 
consequently Mr. Bill Clinton was right when talking about the 
need for a move by the Turkish Cypriot side. 
  Concerning the Skopje issue, Mr. Bill Clinton's statement 
that there should be changes in the views of the regime of the 
Former Yugoslav Republic of "Macedonia" acquires particular 
significance in view of the meeting between Foreign Minister 
Karolos Papoulias and UN mediator Mr. Cyrus Vance. However, it 
would be a mistake to suppose that there has been no pressure on 
the Greek side too to lift economic countermeasures and achieve 
a compromise solution. 
  There are many who doubt that the United States really wants 
to intervene on the side of Greek national interest since our 
country's predicament involves states with which Washington 
either is closely allied, such as Turkey, or is now laying the 
foundations of cooperation, such as Albania and the Republic of 
Skopje. 
  Nevertheless, the U.S. President's statement appears to lift 
the pessimistic atmosphere, but it remains to be seen whether 
Mr. Bill Clinton's interest will lead to concrete results in the 
issues of Cyprus and Skopje. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-19887 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu079_p_94007" </HT>


