<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman: Albania `Reexamining' Embassy Position </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman: Albania `Reexamining' Embassy Position </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2204163194 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2204163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The diplomatic staff of the Greek Embassy in Tirana 
will not leave. Government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos today 
said that Albania is reexamining the measures taken to reduce 
the number of diplomatic staffers at the Greek Embassy. He 
added that, following this development, Greece will decide its 
stance on the issue after a meeting between the foreign 
ministers of the two countries on 3 May in Zurich. Six 
administrative staffers will be leaving the Greek Embassy in 
Tirana. It should be noted that the Greek Embassy in Tirana has 
19 people while the Albanian Embassy in Athens has only one 
administrative staffer out of a total of six people. 
  Replying to questions, the government spokesman said the 
Albanian Government obviously made these decisions after taking 
current developments into consideration. Venizelos also said 
that it should be considered self-explanatory that Mr. van der 
Stoel, as CSCE officer responsible for minority issues, is 
interested in the situation of the Greek minority in Albania. 
  A short while ago, our correspondent in Ioannina, Yeoryios 
Kirousis, reported that the Albanian authorities began releasing 
[from detention] officials of the Greek minority party, Omonoia. 
So far, the president and two members of Omonoia's chapter in 
Gjirokaster have not been released. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

