<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Demirel Comments on Cyprus, Clinton Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Demirel Comments on Cyprus, Clinton Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2304152894 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1435 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2304152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, April 23 (A.A.) -- President Suleyman 
Demirel said on Saturday [23 April] that Turkey is sensitive and 
careful on Cyprus issue, "there could not be anything that is 
against Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus' [TRNC] 
constitution" he added. 
  Asked how he evaluated the U.S. President Bill Clinton's 
words saying there will be important developments within two 
days on Cyprus issue, Demirel said he did not know Clinton's 
statement in detail but "I met TRNC's parliament speaker Halit 
Acarkan and learned that they were discussing the issue of 
confidence-building measures [CBM's]." 
  Acarkan earlier said the UN proposed CBM's for Cyprus have 
been twisted to the advantage of the Greek Cypriot side. 
  He said his state was under great pressure to accept the 
modified version of the CBM's. 
  The points included to the original package of July 1, 1993 
are, giving the roads leading to the uninhabited Maras [Varosha] 
section to the UN control; limitations to be imposed on all 
planes registered in Turkey in the Lefkose [Nicosia] Airport 
which will be opened to international traffic; customs 
procedures to be conducted by an official to be appointed by the 
United Nations to Lefkose Airport and Maras; and the violation 
of the principle that both sides will enjoy equal advantages. 
  Demirel said everyone should accept the two separate 
communities and that these two are the extensions of two 
different nations, should have everything separated, and it is 
not possible to reach a solution by being forced to live 
together. 
  The president said he will visit Egypt in May and he may 
also 
visit Bosnia-Herzegovina to contribute to the peace efforts 
there. 
  Demirel also said he will meet political party leaders on 
May 
4 and discuss the problems of Turkey. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-19895 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu079_q_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Press Center Denies Cyprus Discussed With Clinton </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Press Center Denies Cyprus Discussed With Clinton </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2304185294 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2304185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over still of Prime Minister Tansu </F>
Ciller] 
  [Text] It was reported that Prime Minister Tansu Ciller 
and U.S. President Bill Clinton have definitely not discussed 
the Cyprus issue at a tete-a-tete meeting they had in Washington 
last week. 
  According to a statement issued by the Press Center of the 
President's Office, it was recalled that certain statements 
regarding the Cyprus issue were attributed to Ciller in today's 
issue of a newspaper [not further identified]. The statement 
notes that at the meeting between the delegations held in 
Washington, Clinton stated that there was a deadlock regarding 
the confidence-building measures [CBM's]. 
  Ciller, in turn, said the following at the meeting: The 
original CBM's package was, in principle, approved by the 
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus and was also endorsed by 
Turkey. The package was subsequently changed. It will be 
appropriate to discuss the issue once more before the end of 
April and achieve a rapprochement between the views of the two 
sides. 
  The statement further notes that the minutes of the meeting 
were dispatched to the Foreign Ministry the day of the meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

