<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN's Clark Arrives, Comments on Cyprus Package </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN's Clark Arrives, Comments on Cyprus Package </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2504103294 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1010 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2504103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, April 25 (A.A.) - UN special envoy for 
Cyprus, Joe Clark arrived in Ankara on Sunday [24 April] 
accompanied by his aides Gustave Feissel and John Paul Cavanaugh. 
  Clark said that the confidence-building measures package has 
two points, one being the opening of the uninhabited Maras 
[Varosha] section for Greek settlement under UN supervision, and 
the other being the opening of the Lefkosa [Nicosia] Airport 
also under UN direction, and the partial lifting of the embargo 
imposed on the Turkish side. 
  He said that the former will profit the Greek Cypriots while 
the latter will be to the advantage of the Turkish Cypriots. 
  Clark said these are the last days of the process and that 
he 
has met with Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias in New 
York and is due to meet with Turkish officials in Ankara on 
Monday and Tuesday. 
  He added that he will later meet with leaders of both sides 
and a draft report should at least be prepared before next 
Sunday. 
  Clark said the package will benefit both sides and the 
partial lifting of the embargo will strengthen the Turkish 
Republic of Northern Cyprus' economy by 20 percent. 
  During their stay, Clark, Feissel, and Cavanaugh will meet 
with Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin, Deputy Foreign Minister 
Ozdem Sanberk, and Prime Minister Tansu Ciller but it is not 
definitive as yet. 
  The envoys will leave Turkey early on Wednesday morning. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

