<H3> <TI>   Cindoruk Comments on Political `Crisis' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cindoruk Comments on Political `Crisis' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2204165194 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1555 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2204165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, April 22 (A.A.) -- Parliament Speaker 
Husamettin Cindoruk described today the crisis in Turkey, being 
a political one, rather than economic. `To eliminate the great 
diversity in the country's politics, people should be united 
around principles, not persons,' Cindoruk said. `If they call me 
to duty, because of my 40-year experience in politics, then I 
may resign from my position as parliament speaker, to unite 
them.' 
  In an interview to be aired Saturday [23 April] on TRT-2, 
Cindoruk said that today's problems in Turkey were similar to a 
solar eclipse. 
  The Parliament's public relations office said today that 
during the interview, Cindoruk said Turkey's future will 
`certainly be bright.' 
  `I share the opinion of citizens that there is an excess of 
political parties and this prevents democracy from being 
genuine,' he said. `Mergers among right and left wing parties 
would prevent a political extravagance.' 
  There are 25 political parties registered in Turkey. Of 
these, 11 have seats in parliament. 

</TEXT>

