<H3> <TI>   Comments on Air Strike Decision </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comments on Air Strike Decision </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304111394 Berlin N-TV in German 0945 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2304111394 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin N-TV </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner by </F>
Alexander Privtera after the NATO Council meeting in Brussels on 
22 April--recorded] 
  [Text] [Privtera] Secretary General Woerner, do you 
believe today's decisions will finally convince the Serbs to 
return to the negotiating table and negotiate seriously? 
  [Woerner] I hope so, but to say I believe so would be an 
exaggeration. Above all, we are raising the stakes of their 
aggression. I hope this will at least mean they will think 
about distancing themselves from their policy of unbridled 
aggression particularly against civilians, hospitals, and 
refugee camps. As I say, I cannot express any more than my hope. 
  [Privtera] In the other protection zones, with the exception 
of Gorazde and Sarajevo, there has been no model along the lines 
of the ultimatum for Sarajevo. [sentence as heard] Why this 
solution? Is it perhaps also a concession to Moscow? 
  [Woerner] I would not call it a concession. It does indeed 
give Moscow the possibility, which it already had at the time of 
the first ultimatum for Sarajevo, to talk to the Serbs in an 
effort to convince them to stop attacking safe zones. It will 
not have gone unnoticed that the Russians were disappointed by 
the Bosnian Serbs and their behavior in Gorazde. I can 
therefore well imagine the Russians making their contribution to 
this. But regardless of that, we were the one to make the 
decision, on the advice of the UN secretary general; but the 
decision, as I said, was made by the 16 NATO nations. 

</TEXT>

