<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Terms GATT `Milestone in Trade Policy' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rexrodt Terms GATT `Milestone in Trade Policy' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204101294 Hamburg DPA in German 0756 GMT 22 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2204101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- In the view of FRG Economics Minister 
Guenter Rexrodt, the GATT trade agreement, which was concluded 
in Marrakesh, is of outstanding importance for Germany as an 
export nation. This is a "milestone in trade policy," Rexrodt 
said in a government statement delivered in the Bundestag on 
Friday [22 April]. 
  Thus, the average customs rate for trade with industrial 
goods will decline from 6.3 to 3.9 percent. Particularly 
successful is the agreement about the liberalization of 
services. Here Germany, as the largest exporter of services, 
benefits most since services alone amount to one-quarter of 
Germany's overall exports. In this field are working one-third 
of the 7 million people employed in exports. 
  Rexrodt affirmed his intention to bring the GATT follow-up 
institute, the World Trade Organization, WTO, to Bonn. However, 
Canada, Sweden, and Switzerland are also interested in being the 
headquarters of the new international organization. According 
to the economics minister, tasks still remaining for 
liberalization are the opening up of financial services and 
ocean traffic, and a multilateral steel agreement. 
  On behalf of the Social Democratic Party of Germany, Uwe 
Jens 
stated that the agreement comes more than one year too late. 
What is urgently needed is, above all, an active labor market 
policy in Germany in order to push ahead with reducing 
unemployment and promoting employment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

