<H3> <TI>   Bundestag Approves Compromise on Nursing-Care </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bundestag Approves Compromise on Nursing-Care </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204101494 Hamburg DPA in German 0732 GMT 22 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2204101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- On Friday [22 April] the Bundestag 
finally approved the compromise on the nursing-care insurance 
with the overwhelming majority of the votes from the coalition 
and Social Democratic Party of Germany [SPD] opposition. 
Subject to the approval of the Bundesrat next Friday, which is 
considered certain, the law can come into force on 1 January 
1995. 
  FRG Labor Minister Norbert Bluem (Christian Democratic 
Union) 
said that the implementation of the law will depend on the good 
will and dedication of many people. A law cannot replace human 
readiness for help. 
  Rudolf Dressler, the SPD's chief negotiator, pointed out 
that 
his party has achieved considerable improvements during the 
months of the mediation procedure between the Bundestag and the 
Bundesrat. Now it is the business of the laender to keep the 
promise of abolishing one public holiday to compensate for the 
costs arising for the employers. Gisela Babel (Free Democratic 
Party of Germany) said that it is to her party's credit that the 
nursing-care insurance did "not" turn out to "be larger, 
clumsier, and more expensive." 
  The Party of Democratic Socialism and the Alliance 
90/Greens, 
who had come out in favor of a nursing-care insurance finance 
via taxes, expressed their disappointment. 

</TEXT>

