<H3> <TI>   Daimler-Benz Increases Purchases in New Laender </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daimler-Benz Increases Purchases in New Laender </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204111994 Hamburg DPA in German 0904 GMT 22 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2204111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hannover (DPA) -- In 1993 Daimler-Benz AG 
(Stuttgart) increased the volume of its purchases in the new 
laender by 200 million German marks [DM] compared with the year 
before, thus reaching DM800 million. This exceeded the goal set 
by the company for itself by DM100 million despite the 
recession, Karl Engelhardt, chief coordinator for purchases in 
the corporation, stated at the Hannover Fair on Friday [22 
April]. The plan of buying goods and services for DM1 billion 
from eastern Germany by 1995 will certainly be fulfilled. 
  The corporation has a considerable advantage regarding costs 
by issuing orders in eastern Germany. Ancillary wage costs in 
the west are twice as high as in the new laender. The increase 
in purchases is a sign of the competitiveness of east German 
suppliers. The corporation is buying most in Brandenburg, 
followed by Saxony, Thuringia, Saxony-Anhalt, and 
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania. The northernmost land was able 
to increase its volume by 60 percent last year. 

</TEXT>

