<H3> <TI>   Steinmetz Reportedly Not Involved in RAF Attack </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Steinmetz Reportedly Not Involved in RAF Attack </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2204105894 Hamburg DPA in German 0918 GMT 22 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2204105894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mainz (DPA) -- In the view of Mainz Interior 
Minister Walter Zuber (Social Democratic Party of Germany), 
Klaus Steinmetz, the former liaison official of the 
Rhineland-Palatinate Office for the Protection of the 
Constitution, was not involved in the attack on the new prison 
in Weiterstadt. "According to what I know of the 
investigations, Klaus Steimetz has a watertight alibi for the 
time of the deed," Zuber told the Rhineland-Palatinate Landtag 
on Friday [22 April]. The attack in spring 1993 caused material 
damage of about 130 million marks. 
  Concerning reports about the discovery of traces of 
explosives in the car of the liaison man, who became known in 
connection with the bloody antiterrorist operation in Bad 
Kleinen in June 1993, Zuber said that, according to experts, the 
substance is also used in other compounds. If only very small 
amounts are available, one can hardly distinguish between traces 
of explosives and traces of pharmaceuticals. Stienmetz put the 
authorities on the track of suspected Red Army Faction 
terrorists Wolfgang Grams and Birgit Hogefeld, who were caught 
during the failed police operation in Bad Kleinen. Grams was 
killed during the action. 

</TEXT>

