<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy &amp; Vatican City </F>
<H3> <TI>   Farm Groups Consider GATT Accord `Insufficient' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Farm Groups Consider GATT Accord `Insufficient' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2004125294 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1548 GMT 19 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2004125294 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "GATT: Italian Farm Groups </F>
Criticize Accord"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Rome, April 19 -- A drop in exports, the 
compression of farm income -- with its consequent expulsion from 
the productive cycle of tens of thousands of farming outfits -- 
thereby leaving more and more farmland fallow and unproductive 
are the negative repercussions Italian agriculture must grapple 
with because of the recent accord forged within the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 
  Italian farm organizations consider this accord insufficient 
and in a joint communique, Coldiretti [National Confederation of 
Small Farmers], CIPA [Italian Confederation of Agricultural 
Experts], and Confagricoltura [General Confederation of Italian 
Agriculture] today insisted that the new international regime 
for farm products would prove deleterious for this primary 
sector in Italy and especially for those particularly 
Mediterranean products such as wine, olive oil, olives, fruit 
and vegetables. 
  These organizations are calling for a reform of the relevant 
joint market organizations within the European Union [EU] and 
revised guidelines which take into account the increase in EU 
resources that will be brought about by Community enlargement to 
include Sweden, Norway, Finland and Austria. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

