<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government `Satisfied' With Papandreou-Clinton Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government `Satisfied' With Papandreou-Clinton Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2304123294 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2304123294 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Greek Government is satisfied with Prime 
Minister Andreas Papandreou's meeting with U.S. President Bill 
Clinton at the White House. The prime minister described the 
talks as especially useful. Tilemakhos Khitiris, the deputy 
minister to the prime minister, said the visit was very 
successful. 
  Athens News Agency reported today from Washington that 
according to U.S. evaluations, the lengthy meeting of the U.S. 
President with the prime minister gave the opportunity to the 
two leaders to reconfirm the excellent bilateral relations and 
analyze further the prospects of cooperation in light of the new 
international conditions, particularly in the Balkans. 
  Washington is convinced--the U.S. President has made it 
clear 
to the prime minister--that the White House considers Greece the 
most stable country in the region that can play an important and 
leading role in the Balkans. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

