<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Firmness, Diplomacy Needed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Says Firmness, Diplomacy Needed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2504083394 Paris AFP in English 0804 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2504083394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Paris, April 25 (AFP) -- International policy on 
Bosnia must combine a determined military stance with diplomatic 
doggedness, French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe said Monday [25 
April] in Paris. 
  "We must be firm on the ground and we must be strong-willed, 
I would even say stubborn, to get a diplomatic process that 
works" in Bosnia, Juppe said in a radio interview only hours 
ahead of a meeting in London with his British and U.S. 
counterparts Douglas Hurd and Warren Christopher. 
  The three top diplomats are meeting to prepare talks of the 
three major powers, the United States, Russia and the European 
Union, as well as the United Nations, to define a common policy 
on the Bosnian question. 
  The goal is finally to tell the warring Bosnian parties "to 
come to the negotiating table and talk seriously," Juppe said. 
  Juppe said Bosnian Serbs have acted "savagely, and continue 
to do so, in Gorazde" but that the international community could 
pressure the Bosnian Serb's sponsor Serbia with sanctions "which 
hurt and which should continue to hurt." 
  Juppe said an overall settlement in Bosnia should be based 
on 
the European plan for the former Yugoslav republic to become a 
viable state with institutions that loosely join the Serb, Croat 
and Moslem communities. Territory should also be divided up "in 
order to end the dialogue of the deaf in which we have been 
stuck for months and months." 
  He added that what has happened at Gorazde showed that the 
international community was reacting too slowly and that this 
should be corrected in the future. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

