<H3> <TI>   Serbs Jeer Marchers Protesting Gorazde Shelling </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Jeer Marchers Protesting Gorazde Shelling </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2304161894 Paris AFP in English 1603 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2304161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 23 (AFP) -- An estimated 7,000 people 
marched through Paris Saturday [23 April] to protest the Bosnian 
Serb shelling of the besieged Moslem enclave of Gorazde. 
  Marchers were jeered by a group of around 80 Serb protestors 
denouncing what they called a "witch-hunt" against Bosnian 
Serbs, and police had to intervene to separate the two sides. 
  The march, called by around 20 human rights groups and 
trades 
unions, was led by a number of personalities including writers 
Bernard Henri Levy, Daniel Rondeau and Pascal Bruckner. 
  Organizers said 7,000 people took part in the march. Police 
put the attendance at around 1,200. 
  Demonstrators chanted "Weapons for Bosnia" and "UN, why do 
you let them (the Moslems) be killed?" 
  They called for the use of all means, including military, to 
save the town, which came under renewed Bosnian Serb shelling 
Saturday in defiance of Friday's ultimatum from the North 
Atlantic Treaty Organisation to halt their offensive immediately 
or face air strikes. 

</TEXT>

