<H3> <TI>   Kurdish Leader Talabani Continues Paris Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kurdish Leader Talabani Continues Paris Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets Mitterrand, Juppe, Leotard </H4>

<F P=102> LD2204193994 Paris Radio France International in French 1700 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio France International </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jalal al-Talabani, the leader of the Kurdistan 
Patriotic Union, one of the Kurdish parties in Iraq, was 
received by Francois Mitterrand this morning. The Kurdish 
leader earlier met Defense Minister Francois Leotard and Foreign 
Minister Alain Juppe. This is not the first time Jalal 
al-Talabani has been received in Paris. If he was worried by 
the recent contacts between Paris and Baghdad, he must now feel 
reassured. More details now with Olivier Dalage: 
  [Dalage] Jalal al-Talabani must be satisfied with his trip 
to 
France. The co-chairman of the self-governing Iraqi Kurdistan 
government -- a government self-proclaimed against the Baghdad 
government following the Gulf war -- was received by the most 
important French leaders. Alain Juppe expressed his support for 
respect of Kurdish rights, including respect of their political 
rights, in the framework of Iraq's territorial integrity. For 
his part, the Kurdish leader repeated his plan for a federation 
incorporating broad autonomy of Iraqi Kurdistan in the framework 
of the Iraqi state. The French foreign minister and his 
colleague Defense Minister Francois Leotard both gave assurances 
that France would continue its participation in Operation 
Provide Comfort to protect Iraqi Kurds north of the 62d 
parallel. If Jalal al-Talabani was somewhat apprehensive when 
he arrived following recent contacts between Paris and Baghdad, 
he was told by Juppe not take any notice of rumors because 
France will continue its embargo as long as Iraq will not 
observe all the UN Security Council resolutions. 

</TEXT>

