<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Wants IAEA Observers To Visit Within Month </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Wants IAEA Observers To Visit Within Month </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504132694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1318 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, April 25 KYODO -- North Korea has conveyed 
its desire to have International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
inspectors monitor the refueling of its main nuclear reactor at 
the end of this month, an IAEA source said Monday [25 April]. 
  The source said the IAEA has accepted Pyongyang's proposal 
and plans to send an advance party to North Korea as early as 
Thursday to check and remove security seals on the experimental 
reactor. He said their visas have already been prepared. 
  But the IAEA needs to further sound out North Korea on the 
mission, the source said, noting Pyongyang has yet to reply to 
the Agency's inquiries. 
  He said that before sending a full team, the U.N. nuclear 
watchdog wants to know whether the offer to allow observation of 
the unloading of spent fuel rods at the Yongbyon nuclear 
facility is merely that, or whether North Korea will also allow 
collection of fuel samples to take place. 
  IAEA spokesman David Kyd told reporters Sunday the Agency is 
"not sending a team until we have clarification." 
  The Agency wants to inspect the spent fuel core of the 
Yongbyon reactor to see if any nuclear material has been 
diverted for possible use in a covert nuclear weapons 
development program. 
  Sampling can determine if the spent fuel had been in the 
Yongbyon reactor since it went on line in 1986, or if the fuel 
had been secretly changed. 
  The reactor was shut down for 100 days in 1989, three years 
before the IAEA made its first nuclear inspection in North Korea. 
  The IAEA source said North Korea has not responded to a 
separate agency request that it also be allowed to inspect a 
radiochemical laboratory placed off limits to inspectors in a 
visit last month. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

