<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   GATT Head Desires To Step Down, Cites `Personal' Reasons </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    GATT Head Desires To Step Down, Cites `Personal' Reasons </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504134494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1334 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504134494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 25 KYODO -- GATT chief Peter 
Sutherland, the most likely candidate for the first head of the 
proposed more powerful world trade body, said Monday [25 April] 
he wants to step down, several diplomatic sources said. 
  Sutherland revealed his intention at an informal meeting of 
the heads of delegations of the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade (GATT), citing "personal" matters as the reason for his 
possible resignation. 
  The GATT director general, however, told KYODO NEWS SERVICE 
that he will not officially express his desire to resign soon. 
  "I cannot say anything now," he said. 
  Sutherland succeeded his predecessor Arthur Dunkel in July 
last year and helped lead the Uruguay Round of global trade 
talks to a successful conclusion last December. His term will 
continue until the end of June next year. 
  There have been talks in the last few months that Sutherland 
may leave GATT halfway through his term to land positions at 
bigger international bodies such as the European Union. 
  An Asian diplomatic source said Sutherland said he wants to 
quit after the preparatory work for the World Trade Organization 
[WTO], scheduled to be formed on January 1 next year to replace 
GATT, is completed. 
  Analysts said Sutherland's remarks will soon prompt 
countries 
planning to participate in the WTO to search for other 
candidates for the chief of the new trade body. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

