<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Contradictions in NATO Policy Toward Ex-FRY Seen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Contradictions in NATO Policy Toward Ex-FRY Seen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2504135494 Brussels LA LIBRE BELGIQUE in French 23 Apr 94 
p 6 </F>

<F P=103> BR2504135494 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels LA LIBRE BELGIQUE </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Michel Rosten commentary: "NATO: End of Neutrality"] </F>
  [Text] We cannot question the importance of transatlantic 
relations which, for West Europe, must remain an absolute 
priority. We certainly could not accuse NATO, reduced to merely 
carrying out UN orders, of wanting to take all the credit. 
Nevertheless, we still find it impossible to subscribe to the 
new instant-mix policy drawn up by Washington and registered on 
Friday [22 April] at NATO headquarters by the permanent Council 
of Ambassadors which drew up an ultimatum for the Bosnian Serbs. 
  It is true that the impact of this strong-arm policy will 
please public opinion which was horrified by the Gorazde 
massacre, but the impartial observer must point out its inherent 
contradictions. The West, which wants to bring the Serbs back 
to the negotiating table, has decided, by unusually twisted 
thinking, that the fastest way to do this is by carrying out 
bombing raids that go beyond simply surgical strikes. The 
troops commanded by General Mladic have clearly demonstrated 
after the initial strikes that they will not hesitate to take 
retaliatory action and, consequently, attack blue helmet 
"hostages." 
  The new strategy currently being implemented risks 
escalating 
a conflict in which the Americans refuse to participate on the 
ground. It has to be one thing or the other: Either Washington 
gives a whole new dimension to the Bosnian conflict and sends in 
the U.S. infantry or the White House administration sticks to a 
stance of cautious reserve to preserve UNPROFOR [UN Protection 
Force] neutrality. There is no getting away from the fact that 
a new NATO ultimatum cannot be compared with that issued on 9 
February aimed at lifting the siege of Sarajevo. That one was 
directed at the irregular Serbian troops and Bosnian Government 
forces.... 
  Things have since changed. The whole concept of the 
neutrality of the blue helmets is collapsing. While it is 
acceptable in the name of human rights to impose an 
interventionist force on a country in the throes of civil war, 
is it really justified for NATO to take the side of one of the 
belligerents simply because it is the weaker? Moreover, insofar 
as it does take this decision -- without actually entering the 
war itself to assist "its" blue helmets -- will it not merely 
have accepted the responsibility for prolonging the war? 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-20020 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu080_b_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-080 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Van Rooy Warns Against U.S. Use of Antidumping Rules </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Van Rooy Warns Against U.S. Use of Antidumping Rules </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2504143294 The Hague ECONOMISCHE ZAKEN in Dutch 14 Apr 94 
p 9 </F>

<F P=103> BR2504143294 </F>
<F P=104>  The Hague ECONOMISCHE ZAKEN </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Van Rooy: `Be Careful With Defensive </F>
Trade Rules'"] 
  [Text] "When implementing the GATT/Uruguay Round, we must 
take care not to liberalize trade on the one hand, while on the 
other hand nullifying this effect by enacting new defensive 
trade rules in the area of antidumping and introducing 
protective measures." This warning was made by Economic Affairs 
State Secretary Van Rooy at the ABN/AMRO conference, "Why 
America Now," held in Amsterdam on 7 April. 
  Van Rooy talked about 20 countries which are busy with 
similar plans, and she pointed in particular to the United 
States: "As regards the implementation of the GATT/Uruguay 
Round agreements, the Netherlands will very carefully supervise 
the adaptation of U.S. antidumping legislation. The current 
practice is that complaints by U.S. companies are honored in 
almost all cases by the Department of Commerce. 
  That gives some food for thought. The United States is 
calling for free trade, but there are clear indications that it 
is protecting its own market for certain sensitive products by 
means of antidumping and antisubsidy legislation." According to 
Van Rooy, the United States, as well as the European Union, must 
not give the wrong impression, since that could end up having a 
boomerang effect on their own exports if other countries react 
with their own antidumping rules. 
<H5>  Increasingly Better </H5>
  According to Van Rooy, Netherlands companies are doing 
increasingly better on the North American market. Netherlands 
exports in 1992 totalled 11.5 billion guilders: Around 10 
billion guilders went to the United States; around 900 million 
to Canada; and around 565 million to Mexico. Exports to Mexico, 
in particular, rose sharply and, according to the most recent 
CPB [Central Planning Bureau] estimate, Netherlands exports to 
the United States rose by 25 percent (in value) in 1993. 
  The state secretary expects that Netherlands exports will be 
able to grow further with the implementation of the NAFTA free 
trade agreement and the GATT agreement. 
  Here, she sees opportunities in particular for products such 
as steel, paper, medical equipment, chemicals, pharmaceutical 
products, foodstuffs, (agricultural) machinery, and supply 
industries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-20021 </DOCNO>
