<H3> <TI>   FDP Official Sees Few SPD-CDU Differences </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FDP Official Sees Few SPD-CDU Differences </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2504150594 Hamburg BILD in German 25 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU2504150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg BILD </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Juergen Moellemann, chairman of the North </F>
Rhine-Westphalian FDP, by Rolf Kleine; place and date not given: 
"Moellemann: `He Who Acts Will Make Mistakes!'"] 
  [Text] [Kleine] At the Free Democratic Party [FDP] land 
congress you were reelected chairman with 59.6 percent of the 
vote -- your worst result? 
  [Moellemann] He who wants to make a mark for himself will 
also make mistakes and have critics! This is also true for me. 
One has to live with it. Besides, results of 90 percent are 
abnormal for democracies. More dangerous than the decrease in 
support in the election of a land chairman is the sustained loss 
of votes achieved by the FDP in elections. The question is: 
How can we surmount this low point? 
  [Kleine] How can you? 
  [Moellemann] The FDP must make it clear that we will no 
longer put up with the enormous increase in our horrendous 
national debts! Moreover, we must stimulate the economy and 
create jobs. And the FDP must advocate more strongly the 
reduction of bureaucracy: Fewer ministries! Fewer deputies! 
Fewer laender! 
  [Kleine] Is this a coalition offer to the Social Democratic 
Party of Germany [SPD]? 
  [Moellemann] No! The SPD does not really want to reduce 
bureaucracy and really cut corporate taxes. Yet, one thing is 
true: There are no major differences on central issues between 
the Christian Democratic Union [CDU] and the SPD. 

</TEXT>

